The paper deals with cooperative game theory and approximation algorithms, which are typically studied in the subfield of computational game theory (cs.GT). The use of Monte Carlo methods suggests a focus on artificial intelligence (cs.AI) and machine learning (cs.LG) techniques for approximating the Myerson value. The analysis of the computational complexity of the algorithms and the use of graph theory suggest a connection to algorithms and data structures (cs.DS) and social and information networks (cs.SI).
